The Epicureans rejected the law ot neces· sity and all final cause, supposed that atoms move downward in empty space at the same rate, and assigned the occasion of atoms combining to the sels-movement oi some from their course. In this, without knowing it, they were really attributing psychic properties to the amm, and showed the influence of the old hylozoistic conception of matter. Although they utilized this voluntary power ol the atom only in explaining the lreedom of the will, believing that everything in nature goes on rigidly in . obedience to law, the principle thus introduced was not lost sight ol, but wras carried to its fullest application in the gradual spiritualization ol the atom. lt was enlarged upon by Bruno‚ in the doctrine that “the elementary parts of all that exists are the minima or monads‚ which are to be considered as points, not absolutely unextended‚ but spherical; they are at once psychical and material.’' It permeates the system of Gas- sendi, who, though he clai-med simply to revive Epicureanism‚ “ascribed to the atoms force and even sensation.’'1 lt found a complete and final realization in the monadology of Leibnitz. For in opposition to Spinoza’s doctrine oi one universal substance with the attributes of thought and extension‚ Leibnitz assumed a plurality oi elementary forms which he made out to be in· divisible points or penicles, “punctual unities,’' qualitatively different, each having a soul ot its own and bearing to the sum of all a fixed relation in a system of universal harmony. As he emphasized the spiritual side oi these psychic atoms or monads‚ his tendency was idealistic; and his doctrine marks a transition from Materialism to Idealism. Bruno, Gassendi, and Leibnitz accepted the Christian conception ol God, but seem to have found it adifficult matter to reconcile this with their philosophy.
